   "source": [
    "## Final comparison between minimum-variance and mean-variance portfolios\n",
    "\n",
    "The analytical minimum-variance portfolio and the mean-variance portfolios from Exercise 1.c are not expected to coincide, because they solve different optimization problems.\n",
    "\n",
    "The **minimum-variance** problem is\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\min_w \\; w^\\top \\Sigma w\n",
    "\\quad \\text{s.t.} \\quad \\mathbf{1}^\\top w = 1\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "so it only minimizes portfolio risk. Expected returns do not enter the objective, and the solution is the fully invested portfolio with the lowest possible variance.\n",
    "\n",
    "The **mean-variance** problem is\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\min_w \\; \\frac{\\lambda}{2} w^\\top \\Sigma w - \\mu^\\top w\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "subject to the relevant constraints, where $\\mu$ is the vector of expected returns and $\\lambda$ is the risk-aversion parameter. In this case, the optimizer trades off risk against return, so it may accept higher variance in order to achieve higher expected performance.\n",
    "\n",
    "This difference in the objective functions explains the empirical results. The analytical minimum-variance portfolio has the lowest variance and volatility, while the mean-variance portfolios generally achieve higher expected returns at the cost of higher risk. The weight-distance measures also show that the allocations are materially different, confirming that the two methods lead to genuinely different portfolios.\n",
    "\n",
    "A final remark is that the comparison is not perfectly homogeneous, since the mean-variance portfolios in Exercise 1.c are computed under additional box and group constraints, whereas the analytical minimum-variance solution only uses the budget constraint. Even so, the comparison remains informative: the minimum-variance portfolio is the benchmark risk-minimizing allocation, while the mean-variance portfolios move away from it in order to improve expected return."
   ]
  },
