    "## **Appendix:** Metrics used to assess the quality of a quadratic optimization solution\n",
    "\n",
    "To evaluate the quality of a computed solution, the following metrics are considered.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1. Objective value\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider the quadratic optimization problem\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\min_x \\; \\frac{1}{2} x^\\top P x + q^\\top x\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "subject to the equality constraints\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "Ax = b .\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The objective value associated with a candidate solution \\(x\\) is therefore\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "f(x) = \\frac{1}{2} x^\\top P x + q^\\top x .\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This quantity measures the value of the optimization criterion at the computed solution.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2. Primal residual\n",
    "\n",
    "The primal residual measures how accurately the equality constraints are satisfied. It is defined as the infinity norm of the constraint violation:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "r_{\\mathrm{primal}} = \\|Ax - b\\|_\\infty .\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "A value close to zero indicates that the candidate solution is nearly feasible with respect to the primal constraints.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 3. Dual residual\n",
    "\n",
    "The dual residual measures the violation of the stationarity condition in the Karush-Kuhn-Tucker (KKT) system. For an equality-constrained quadratic problem, the stationarity condition is\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "Px + q + A^\\top \\lambda = 0 ,\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\lambda$ denotes the vector of Lagrange multipliers associated with the equality constraints. The dual residual is thus computed as\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "r_{\\mathrm{dual}} = \\|Px + q + A^\\top \\lambda\\|_\\infty .\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "A value close to zero indicates that the first-order optimality condition is well satisfied.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 4. Duality gap\n",
    "\n",
    "The duality gap measures the difference between the primal objective value and the dual objective value.\n",
    "\n",
    "The primal objective is\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "f(x) = \\frac{1}{2} x^\\top P x + q^\\top x .\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The corresponding dual objective for the equality-constrained quadratic problem is\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "g(\\lambda) = -\\frac{1}{2}(q + A^\\top \\lambda)^\\top P^{-1}(q + A^\\top \\lambda) - b^\\top \\lambda .\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The duality gap is then defined as\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{gap} = f(x) - g(\\lambda) .\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "For an optimal solution, this quantity should be equal, or very close, to zero.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 5. Runtime\n",
    "\n",
    "The runtime measures the total computation time required to obtain the solution:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{runtime} = t_{\\mathrm{end}} - t_{\\mathrm{start}} .\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This metric is useful to assess the computational efficiency of the optimization method.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Interpretation\n",
    "\n",
    "A high-quality solution is characterized by:\n",
    "\n",
    "- a small primal residual, indicating near-feasibility of the constraints,\n",
    "- a small dual residual, indicating that the stationarity condition is nearly satisfied,\n",
    "- a negligible duality gap, indicating consistency between primal and dual solutions,\n",
    "- and a low runtime, indicating computational efficiency."
   ]
  }
